# Stable Sort in JavaScript

## Modern Approach (ES2019+)
JavaScript's `Array.sort()` is **guaranteed to be stable** since ES2019 (ES10), so you can use it directly:

```javascript
const data = [
  { name: 'John', age: 30 },
  { name: 'Jane', age: 30 },
  { name: 'Bob', age: 25 }
];

// Stable sort by age
const sorted = data.sort((a, b) => a.age - b.age);
console.log(sorted);
// [{ name: 'Bob', age: 25 }, { name: 'John', age: 30 }, { name: 'Jane', age: 30 }]
// John stays before Jane (original order preserved for equal elements)
```

## Legacy Approach (Pre-ES2019)
For older environments, implement your own stable sort:

```javascript
function stableSort(arr, compareFn) {
  // Create array of [element, originalIndex] pairs
  const indexed = arr.map((el, i) => [el, i]);

  // Sort using compareFn, but use index for ties
  indexed.sort((a, b) => {
    const cmp = compareFn(a[0], b[0]);
    return cmp !== 0 ? cmp : a[1] - b[1];
  });

  // Extract the elements
  return indexed.map(el => el[0]);
}

const sorted = stableSort(data, (a, b) => a.age - b.age);
```

## Why This Matters
Stable sorting preserves the original relative order of elements with equal sort keys:

```javascript
const items = [{ id: 1, priority: 'high' }, { id: 2, priority: 'high' }];

// With stable sort: id 1 stays before id 2
items.sort((a, b) => a.priority.localeCompare(b.priority));
```

**Recommendation:** Use native `Array.sort()` for modern codebases. Only implement a custom stable sort if you need to support very old browsers.

# Stable Sort in JavaScript

## Modern Approach (Recommended)

**JavaScript's `Array.sort()` is guaranteed to be stable since ES2019 (ES10).**

```javascript
const arr = [
  { name: 'John', age: 30 },
  { name: 'Jane', age: 25 },
  { name: 'Bob', age: 30 },
];

// Stable sort by age
arr.sort((a, b) => a.age - b.age);

// Result maintains original order for equal elements:
// Jane (25), John (30), Bob (30) ← order of John and Bob preserved
```

## Key Points

✅ **`sort()` is stable** - equal elements maintain their original relative order  
✅ **Works in-place** - modifies the original array  
✅ **Widely supported** - all modern browsers and Node.js

## If You Need Immutable Sorting

Use spread operator or `slice()`:

```javascript
const arr = [3, 1, 2, 1];

// Creates new array, leaves original unchanged
const sorted = [...arr].sort((a, b) => a - b);
```

## Complex Example

```javascript
const students = [
  { name: 'Alice', score: 85, id: 1 },
  { name: 'Bob', score: 85, id: 2 },
  { name: 'Charlie', score: 90, id: 3 },
];

// Sort by score (ascending), keeps original order for same scores
students.sort((a, b) => a.score - b.score);

// Result: Alice (85, id:1), Bob (85, id:2), Charlie (90, id:3)
```

## Legacy Workaround (Pre-ES2019)

If supporting very old browsers, add index tracking:

```javascript
const arr = [3, 1, 2, 1];

const stableSorted = arr
  .map((val, idx) => ({ val, idx }))
  .sort((a, b) => a.val - b.val || a.idx - b.idx)
  .map(({ val }) => val);
```

**Modern browsers?** Just use `.sort()` — it's stable! 🎯

# Stable Sort in JavaScript

## Modern JavaScript (ES2019+)
The easiest way is to use **`Array.sort()` with a stable comparison function**, as JavaScript engines now guarantee stable sorts.

```javascript
const arr = [
  { name: 'John', age: 30 },
  { name: 'Jane', age: 25 },
  { name: 'Bob', age: 30 }
];

// Stable sort by age
arr.sort((a, b) => a.age - b.age);
console.log(arr);
// Objects with same age maintain original order
```

## Why Built-in Sort is Now Stable

All modern JavaScript engines implement **stable sorting** (guaranteed since ES2019):
- Chrome/V8: Stable
- Firefox: Stable
- Safari: Stable
- Node.js: Stable

## Explicit Stable Sort Implementation

If you need to support older browsers or want explicit control:

```javascript
function stableSort(arr, compareFn) {
  // Create array of [value, originalIndex] pairs
  return arr
    .map((value, index) => ({ value, index }))
    .sort((a, b) => {
      const comparison = compareFn(a.value, b.value);
      // If equal, maintain original order
      return comparison !== 0 ? comparison : a.index - b.index;
    })
    .map(({ value }) => value);
}

// Usage
const result = stableSort(arr, (a, b) => a.age - b.age);
```

## Comparison: Stable vs Unstable

```javascript
const data = [
  { name: 'A', priority: 2 },
  { name: 'B', priority: 1 },
  { name: 'C', priority: 2 }
];

data.sort((a, b) => a.priority - b.priority);

// Stable result: B(1), A(2), C(2) ← A stays before C
// Unstable could give: B(1), C(2), A(2) ← order changed
```

## Key Takeaway
✅ **Just use `Array.sort()` normally** - modern JavaScript guarantees stability by default.

# Stable Sort in JavaScript

## Modern Approach (ES2019+)

**Good news**: `Array.sort()` is **guaranteed to be stable** since ES2019.

```javascript
const arr = [
  { name: 'John', age: 30 },
  { name: 'Jane', age: 25 },
  { name: 'Bob', age: 30 }
];

// Stable sort by age
arr.sort((a, b) => a.age - b.age);
// Result preserves original order for equal elements
```

## If You Need to Support Older Browsers

### 1. **Merge Sort** (guaranteed stable)
```javascript
function mergeSort(arr, compareFn) {
  if (arr.length <= 1) return arr;

  const mid = Math.floor(arr.length / 2);
  const left = mergeSort(arr.slice(0, mid), compareFn);
  const right = mergeSort(arr.slice(mid), compareFn);

  return merge(left, right, compareFn);
}

function merge(left, right, compareFn) {
  const result = [];
  let i = 0, j = 0;

  while (i < left.length && j < right.length) {
    if (compareFn(left[i], right[j]) <= 0) {
      result.push(left[i++]);
    } else {
      result.push(right[j++]);
    }
  }

  return result.concat(left.slice(i)).concat(right.slice(j));
}

// Usage
const sorted = mergeSort(arr, (a, b) => a.age - b.age);
```

### 2. **Add Index Tracking** (works with any sort)
```javascript
const arr = [{ id: 1 }, { id: 2 }, { id: 1 }];

// Add original indices
const indexed = arr.map((item, index) => ({ item, index }));

// Sort by item, then by original index if equal
indexed.sort((a, b) => {
  const cmp = a.item.id - b.item.id;
  return cmp !== 0 ? cmp : a.index - b.index;
});

// Extract original items
const result = indexed.map(x => x.item);
```

## Quick Comparison

| Method | Modern Browser | Old Browser | Performance |
|--------|---|---|---|
| `Array.sort()` | ✅ Stable | ❌ Unstable | Fast |
| Merge Sort | ✅ Stable | ✅ Stable | O(n log n) |
| Index Tracking | ✅ Stable | ✅ Stable | O(n log n) |

## Recommendation

**Use `Array.sort()` directly** unless you need to support very old browsers (IE, old Node.js versions < 12).

# Stable Sort in JavaScript

## Modern Solution (ES2019+)

JavaScript's `Array.sort()` has been **guaranteed stable since ES2019**, so you can use it directly:

```javascript
const arr = [
  { name: 'John', age: 30 },
  { name: 'Jane', age: 25 },
  { name: 'Bob', age: 30 }
];

// Stable sort by age
arr.sort((a, b) => a.age - b.age);
console.log(arr);
// Maintains original order for equal elements (John stays before Bob)
```

## For Older Browsers

If you need to support older environments, implement your own stable sort:

### Merge Sort (Classic Approach)

```javascript
function mergeSort(arr, compareFn) {
  if (arr.length <= 1) return arr;

  const mid = Math.floor(arr.length / 2);
  const left = mergeSort(arr.slice(0, mid), compareFn);
  const right = mergeSort(arr.slice(mid), compareFn);

  return merge(left, right, compareFn);
}

function merge(left, right, compareFn) {
  const result = [];
  let i = 0, j = 0;

  while (i < left.length && j < right.length) {
    if (compareFn(left[i], right[j]) <= 0) {
      result.push(left[i++]);
    } else {
      result.push(right[j++]);
    }
  }

  return result.concat(left.slice(i), right.slice(j));
}

// Usage
const arr = [3, 1, 4, 1, 5];
const sorted = mergeSort(arr, (a, b) => a - b);
console.log(sorted); // [1, 1, 3, 4, 5]
```

### Index-Based Approach

```javascript
function stableSort(arr, compareFn) {
  // Add original indices
  const indexed = arr.map((val, idx) => ({ val, idx }));

  // Sort with index as tiebreaker
  indexed.sort((a, b) => {
    const cmp = compareFn(a.val, b.val);
    return cmp !== 0 ? cmp : a.idx - b.idx;
  });

  // Extract values
  return indexed.map(item => item.val);
}

// Usage
const arr = [{ id: 2 }, { id: 1 }, { id: 2 }];
const sorted = stableSort(arr, (a, b) => a.id - b.id);
```

## Summary

| Approach | Browser Support | Recommendation |
|----------|-----------------|-----------------|
| Native `.sort()` | Modern browsers (ES2019+) | ✅ **Use this** |
| Merge Sort | All browsers | Heavy computation |
| Index-based | All browsers | Good fallback |

**Best practice:** Use native `.sort()` and provide a polyfill for legacy support if needed.

# Stable Sort in JavaScript

## Modern JavaScript (ES2019+)

**Good news**: `Array.sort()` is **guaranteed to be stable** since ES2019.

```javascript
const arr = [
  { name: 'John', age: 30 },
  { name: 'Jane', age: 25 },
  { name: 'Bob', age: 30 }
];

// Stable sort by age
arr.sort((a, b) => a.age - b.age);
// Result maintains original order for equal elements
```

## If You Need to Support Older Browsers

### Using `localeCompare()` (Strings)
```javascript
const words = ['zebra', 'apple', 'banana', 'apple'];
words.sort((a, b) => a.localeCompare(b));
// Stable and maintains order of equal elements
```

### Merge Sort (Guaranteed Stable)
```javascript
function mergeSort(arr, compareFn = (a, b) => a - b) {
  if (arr.length <= 1) return arr;

  const mid = Math.floor(arr.length / 2);
  const left = mergeSort(arr.slice(0, mid), compareFn);
  const right = mergeSort(arr.slice(mid), compareFn);

  return merge(left, right, compareFn);
}

function merge(left, right, compareFn) {
  const result = [];
  let i = 0, j = 0;

  while (i < left.length && j < right.length) {
    if (compareFn(left[i], right[j]) <= 0) {
      result.push(left[i++]);
    } else {
      result.push(right[j++]);
    }
  }

  return result.concat(left.slice(i)).concat(right.slice(j));
}

// Usage
const data = [
  { name: 'John', score: 90 },
  { name: 'Jane', score: 85 },
  { name: 'Bob', score: 90 }
];

mergeSort(data, (a, b) => a.score - b.score);
```

## Test Stability

```javascript
const arr = [
  { id: 1, priority: 'high' },
  { id: 2, priority: 'low' },
  { id: 3, priority: 'high' }
];

arr.sort((a, b) => a.priority.localeCompare(b.priority));

// If stable: id order within same priority is preserved
console.log(arr);
// [
//   { id: 1, priority: 'high' },
//   { id: 3, priority: 'high' },
//   { id: 2, priority: 'low' }
// ]
```

## Summary

| Scenario | Solution |
|----------|----------|
| Modern JS (ES2019+) | Use `Array.sort()` directly |
| Strings | Use `.localeCompare()` |
| Old browsers | Implement merge sort |

**For most cases today**, `Array.sort()` is your answer! 🎯
